# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: faiss
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] The **curse of dimensionality** refers to various phenomena that arise when analyzing and organizing data in high-dimensional spaces that do not occur in low-dimensional settings such as the three-dimensional physical space of everyday experience.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Bellman when considering problems in dynamic programming.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] The curse generally refers to issues that arise when the number of datapoints is small (in a suitably defined sense) relative to the intrinsic dimension of the data.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Dimensionally cursed phenomena occur in domains such as numerical analysis, sampling, combinatorics, machine learning, data mining and databases.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] The common theme of these problems is that when the dimensionality increases, the volume of the space increases so fast that the available data becomes sparse.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In order to obtain a reliable result, the amount of data needed often grows exponentially with the dimensionality.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Also, organizing and searching data often relies on detecting areas where objects form groups with similar properties; in high dimensional data, however, all objects appear to be sparse and dissimilar in many ways, which prevents common data organization strategies from being efficient.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In some problems, each variable can take one of several discrete values, or the range of possible values is divided to give a finite number of possibilities.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Taking the variables together, a huge number of combinations of values must be considered.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This effect is also known as the combinatorial explosion.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Even in the simplest case of d binary variables, the number of possible combinations already is $2^{d}$ , exponential in the dimensionality.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Naively, each additional dimension doubles the effort needed to try all combinations.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] There is an exponential increase in volume associated with adding extra dimensions to a mathematical space.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In general, with a spacing distance of 10−*n* the 10-dimensional hypercube appears to be a factor of 10*n*(10−1) = [(10*n*)10/(10*n*)] "larger" than the 1-dimensional hypercube, which is the unit interval.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In the above example *n* = 2: when using a sampling distance of 0.01 the 10-dimensional hypercube appears to be 1018 "larger" than the unit interval.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This effect is a combination of the combinatorics problems above and the distance function problems explained below.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] When solving dynamic optimization problems by numerical backward induction, the objective function must be evaluated for each combination of values in a discretized state space.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This is a significant obstacle when the dimension of the "state variable" is large.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In an abstract sense, as the number of features or dimensions grows, the amount of data we need to generalize accurately grows exponentially.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] A typical rule of thumb is that there should be at least 5 training examples for each dimension in the representation.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In machine learning and insofar as predictive performance is concerned, the *curse of dimensionality* is used interchangeably with the *peaking phenomenon*, which is also known as *Hughes phenomenon*.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In other words, both the size of additional features and their (relative) cumulative discriminatory effect are important in observing a decrease or increase in the average predictive power.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In metric learning, higher dimensions can sometimes allow a model to achieve better performance.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] After normalizing embeddings to the surface of a hypersphere, FaceNet achieves the best performance using 128 dimensions as opposed to 64, 256, or 512 dimensions in one ablation study.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] A loss function for unitary-invariant dissimilarity between word embeddings was found to be minimized in high dimensions.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In data mining, the curse of dimensionality refers to a data set with too many features.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Consider the first table, which depicts 200 individuals and 2000 genes (features) with a 1 or 0 denoting whether or not they have a genetic mutation in that gene.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] A data mining application to this data set may be finding the correlation between specific genetic mutations and creating a classification algorithm such as a decision tree to determine whether an individual has cancer or not.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] A common practice of data mining in this domain would be to create association rules between genetic mutations that lead to the development of cancers.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] To do this, one would have to loop through each genetic mutation of each individual and find other genetic mutations that occur over a desired threshold and create pairs.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] They would start with pairs of two, then three, then four until they result in an empty set of pairs.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] The complexity of this algorithm can lead to calculating all permutations of gene pairs for each individual or row.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Given the formula for calculating the permutations of n items with a group size of r is: ${\frac {n!}{(n-r)!}}$ , calculating the number of three pair permutations of any given individual would be 7988004000 different pairs of genes to evaluate for each individual.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] The number of pairs created will grow by an order of factorial as the size of the pairs increase.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] The growth is depicted in the permutation table (see right).
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] As we can see from the permutation table above, one of the major problems data miners face regarding the curse of dimensionality is that the space of possible parameter values grows exponentially or factorially as the number of features in the data set grows.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This problem critically affects both computational time and space when searching for associations or optimal features to consider.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Another problem data miners may face when dealing with too many features is that the number of false predictions or classifications tends to increase as the number of features grows in the data set.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In terms of the classification problem discussed above, keeping every data point could lead to a higher number of false positives and false negatives in the model.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This may seem counterintuitive, but consider the genetic mutation table from above, depicting all genetic mutations for each individual.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Each genetic mutation, whether they correlate with cancer or not, will have some input or weight in the model that guides the decision-making process of the algorithm.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] There may be mutations that are outliers or ones that dominate the overall distribution of genetic mutations when in fact they do not correlate with cancer.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] These features may be working against one's model, making it more difficult to obtain optimal results.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This problem is up to the data miner to solve, and there is no universal solution.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] The first step any data miner should take is to explore the data, in an attempt to gain an understanding of how it can be used to solve the problem.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] One must first understand what the data means, and what they are trying to discover before they can decide if anything must be removed from the data set.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Then they can create or use a feature selection or dimensionality reduction algorithm to remove samples or features from the data set if they deem it necessary.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] One example of such methods is the interquartile range method, used to remove outliers in a data set by calculating the standard deviation of a feature or occurrence.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] When a measure such as a Euclidean distance is defined using many coordinates, there is little difference in the distances between different pairs of points.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] As the dimension d of the space increases, the hypersphere becomes an insignificant volume relative to that of the hypercube.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Furthermore, the distance between the center and the corners is $r{\sqrt {d}}$ , which increases without bound for fixed r.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In this sense when points are uniformly generated in a high-dimensional hypercube, almost all points are much farther than r units away from the center.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In high dimensions, the volume of the *d*-dimensional unit hypercube (with coordinates of the vertices $\pm 1$ ) is concentrated near a sphere with the radius ${\sqrt {d}}/{\sqrt {3}}$ for large dimension *d*.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Therefore, the squared distance from the origin, ${\textstyle r^{2}=\sum _{i}x_{i}^{2}}$ has the average value *d*/3 and variance 4*d*/45.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] For large *d*, distribution of $r^{2}/d$ is close to the normal distribution with the mean 1/3 and the standard deviation $2/{\sqrt {45d}}$ according to the central limit theorem.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Thus, when uniformly generating points in high dimensions, both the "middle" of the hypercube, and the corners are empty, and all the volume is concentrated near the surface of a sphere of "intermediate" radius ${\textstyle {\sqrt {d/3}}}$ .
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This also helps to understand the chi-squared distribution.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Indeed, the (non-central) chi-squared distribution associated to a random point in the interval [-1, 1] is the same as the distribution of the length-squared of a random point in the *d*-cube.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] By the law of large numbers, this distribution concentrates itself in a narrow band around *d* times the standard deviation squared (σ2) of the original derivation.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This illuminates the chi-squared distribution and also illustrates that most of the volume of the *d*-cube concentrates near the boundary of a sphere of radius $\sigma {\sqrt {d}}$ .
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] A further development of this phenomenon is as follows.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Any fixed distribution on the real numbers induces a product distribution on points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ .
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This is often cited as distance functions losing their usefulness (for the nearest-neighbor criterion in feature-comparison algorithms, for example) in high dimensions.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] However, recent research has shown this to only hold in the artificial scenario when the one-dimensional distributions $\mathbb {R}$ are independent and identically distributed.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] When attributes are correlated, data can become easier and provide higher distance contrast and the signal-to-noise ratio was found to play an important role, thus feature selection should be used.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] More recently, it has been suggested that there may be a conceptual flaw in the argument that contrast-loss creates a curse in high dimensions.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Machine learning can be understood as the problem of assigning instances to their respective generative process of origin, with class labels acting as symbolic representations of individual generative processes.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] The curse's derivation assumes all instances are independent, identical outcomes of a single high dimensional generative process.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] If there is only one generative process, there would exist only one (naturally occurring) class and machine learning would be conceptually ill-defined in both high and low dimensions.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Thus, the traditional argument that contrast-loss creates a curse, may be fundamentally inappropriate.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In addition, it has been shown that when the generative model is modified to accommodate multiple generative processes, contrast-loss can morph from a curse to a blessing, as it ensures that the nearest-neighbor of an instance is almost-surely its most closely related instance.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] From this perspective, contrast-loss makes high dimensional distances especially meaningful and not especially non-meaningful as is often argued.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] The effect complicates nearest neighbor search in high dimensional space.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] It is not possible to quickly reject candidates by using the difference in one coordinate as a lower bound for a distance based on all the dimensions.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] However, it has recently been observed that the mere number of dimensions does not necessarily result in difficulties, since *relevant* additional dimensions can also increase the contrast.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In addition, for the resulting ranking it remains useful to discern close and far neighbors.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Irrelevant ("noise") dimensions, however, reduce the contrast in the manner described above.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In time series analysis, where the data are inherently high-dimensional, distance functions also work reliably as long as the signal-to-noise ratio is high enough.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Another effect of high dimensionality on distance functions concerns *k*-nearest neighbor (*k*-NN) graphs constructed from a data set using a distance function.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] As the dimension increases, the indegree distribution of the *k*-NN digraph becomes skewed with a peak on the right because of the emergence of a disproportionate number of **hubs**, that is, data-points that appear in many more *k*-NN lists of other data-points than the average.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This phenomenon can have a considerable impact on various techniques for classification (including the *k*-NN classifier), semi-supervised learning, and clustering, and it also affects information retrieval.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Hubness: certain objects occur more frequently in neighbor lists than others.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Many of the analyzed specialized methods tackle one or another of these problems, but there remain many open research questions.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Despite the expected "curse of dimensionality" difficulties, common-sense heuristics based on the most straightforward methods "can yield results which are almost surely optimal" for high-dimensional problems.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] The term "blessing of dimensionality" was introduced in the late 1990s.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Donoho in his "Millennium manifesto" explained why he thinks the "blessing of dimensionality" will form a basis of future data mining.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] The effects of the blessing of dimensionality were discovered in many applications and found their foundation in the concentration of measure phenomena.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] One example of the blessing of dimensionality phenomenon is linear separability of a random point from a large finite random set with high probability even if this set is exponentially large: the number of elements in this random set can grow exponentially with dimension.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] Moreover, this linear functional can be selected in the form of the simplest linear Fisher discriminant.
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This separability theorem was proven for a wide class of probability distributions: general uniformly log-concave distributions, product distributions in a cube and many other families (reviewed recently in ).
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] This property significantly simplifies the expected geometry of data and indexing of high-dimensional data (blessing), but, at the same time, it makes the similarity search in high dimensions difficult and even useless (curse).
[src:faiss/curse-of-dimensionality] In particular for unsupervised data analysis this effect is known as swamping.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] Faiss is a library for efficient similarity search and clustering of dense vectors.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] It contains algorithms that search in sets of vectors of any size, up to ones that possibly do not fit in RAM.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] It also contains supporting code for evaluation and parameter tuning.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] Faiss is written in C++ with complete wrappers for Python (versions 2 and 3).
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] Some of the most useful algorithms are implemented on the GPU.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] It is developed primarily at Meta AI Research with help from external contributors.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] Given a set of vectors $\{ x_1,..., x_n \}$ in dimension $d$, Faiss builds a data structure in RAM.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] where $\lVert.\rVert$ is the Euclidean distance (L2).
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] In Faiss terms, the data structure is an *index*, an object that has an *add* method to add x_i vector.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] Note that the dimension of x_i is assumed to be fixed.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] Computing the argmin is the *search* operation on the index.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] A general paper about product quantization and related methods: "A Survey of Product Quantization", Yusuke Matsui, Yusuke Uchida, Hervé Jégou, Shin’ichi Satoh, ITE transactions on MTA, 2018.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] Methods that are implemented in Faiss are highlighted in red (2021-08-19: additionally implemented: SIMD options and additive quantization).
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] Image credit: Yusuke Matsui, thanks for allowing us to use it!
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] This wiki contains high-level information about Faiss and a tutorial.
[src:faiss/facebookresearch-faiss] Most examples are in Python for brievity, but the C++ API is exactly the same, so the translation for one to the other is trivial most of the times.
[src:faiss/faiss-ai] Faiss is written in C++ with complete wrappers for Python.
[src:faiss/faiss-ai] It is developed primarily at FAIR, the fundamental AI research team of Meta.
[src:faiss/faiss-ai] Note that either package should be installed, but not both, as the latter is a superset of the former.
[src:faiss/faiss-ai] A general paper about product quantization and related methods: “A Survey of Product Quantization”, Yusuke Matsui, Yusuke Uchida, Hervé Jégou, Shin’ichi Satoh, ITE transactions on MTA, 2018.
[src:faiss/faiss-ai] Methods that are implemented in Faiss are highlighted in red.
[src:faiss/faiss-ai] See the Terms of Use and Privacy Policy.
[src:faiss/faiss] FAISS is written in C++ with complete wrappers for Python and C.
[src:faiss/faiss] Some of the most useful algorithms are implemented on the GPU using CUDA.
[src:faiss/faiss] FAISS is organized as a toolbox that contains a variety of indexing methods that commonly involve a chain of components (preprocessing, compression, non-exhaustive search, etc.).
[src:faiss/faiss] The scope of the library is intentionally limited to focus on ANNS algorithmic implementation and to avoid facilities related to database functionality, distributed computing or feature extraction algorithms.
[src:faiss/faiss] FAISS focuses on euclidean distance and inner product distance for floating-point data.
[src:faiss/faiss] The limited support of other distances (manhattan distance, Lp distance, etc.) is also available.
[src:faiss/faiss] FAISS code supports multithreading via OpenMP, utilizes BLAS via OpenBLAS or Intel MKL, and also uses custom SIMD kernels for x86 and ARM Neon CPUs.
[src:faiss/faiss] FAISS has a standalone *Vector Codec* functionality for the lossy compression of vectors, allowing to trade the representation accuracy for the binary size.
[src:faiss/faiss] Typical FAISS applications include recommender systems, data mining, text retrieval and content moderation.
[src:faiss/faiss] FAISS was reported to index 1.5 trillion 144-dimensional vectors for internal Meta Platforms applications.
[src:faiss/faiss] FAISS is used in vector databases as a core component of a search engine (OpenSearch, Milvus, Vearch).
[src:faiss/faiss] FAISS is often considered as a baseline in similarity search benchmarks.
[src:faiss/faiss] FAISS has an integration with Haystack, LangChain frameworks.
[src:faiss/faiss] Various advanced code snippets for FAISS can be found on its snippets wiki page and case studies wiki page.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] In computer science, a ***k*-d tree** (short for *k-dimensional tree*) is a space-partitioning data structure for organizing points in a *k*-dimensional space.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] K-dimensional is that which concerns exactly k orthogonal axes or a space of any number of dimensions.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] The *k*-d tree is a binary tree in which *every* node is a *k*-dimensional point.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Every non-leaf node can be thought of as implicitly generating a splitting hyperplane that divides the space into two parts, known as half-spaces.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Points to the left of this hyperplane are represented by the left subtree of that node and points to the right of the hyperplane are represented by the right subtree.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] The hyperplane direction is chosen in the following way: every node in the tree is associated with one of the *k* dimensions, with the hyperplane perpendicular to that dimension's axis.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] So, for example, if for a particular split the "x" axis is chosen, all points in the subtree with a smaller "x" value than the node will appear in the left subtree and all points with a larger "x" value will be in the right subtree.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] In such a case, the hyperplane would be set by the x value of the point, and its normal would be the unit x-axis.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Since there are many possible ways to choose axis-aligned splitting planes, there are many different ways to construct *k*-d trees.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] This method leads to a balanced *k*-d tree, in which each leaf node is approximately the same distance from the root.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] However, balanced trees are not necessarily optimal for all applications.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Note that it is not *required* to select the median point.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] In the case where median points are not selected, there is no guarantee that the tree will be balanced.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] To avoid coding a complex $O(n)$ median-finding algorithm or using an $O(n\log(n))$ sort such as heapsort or mergesort to sort all *n* points, a popular practice is to sort a *fixed* number of *randomly* *selected* points, and use the median of those points to serve as the splitting plane.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] In practice, this technique often results in nicely balanced trees.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Given a list of *n* points, the following algorithm uses a median-finding sort to construct a balanced *k*-d tree containing those points.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] It is common that points "after" the median include only the ones that are strictly greater than the median in the current dimension.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] For points that lie on the median in the current dimension, it is possible to define a function that compares them in all dimensions.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] In some cases, it is acceptable to let points equal to the median lie on one side of the median, for example, by splitting the points into a "lesser than" subset and a "greater than or equal to" subset.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] This algorithm creates the invariant that for any node, all the nodes in the left subtree are on one side of a splitting plane, and all the nodes in the right subtree are on the other side.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Points that lie on the splitting plane may appear on either side.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] The splitting plane of a node goes through the point associated with that node (referred to in the code as *node.location*).
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Alternative algorithms for building a balanced *k*-d tree presort the data prior to building the tree.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Then, they maintain the order of the presort during tree construction and hence eliminate the costly step of finding the median at each level of subdivision.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Two such algorithms build a balanced *k*-d tree to sort triangles in order to improve the execution time of ray tracing for three-dimensional computer graphics.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] These algorithms presort *n* triangles prior to building the *k*-d tree, then build the tree in $O(n\log n)$ time in the best case.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] An algorithm that builds a balanced *k*-d tree to sort points has a worst-case complexity of $O(kn\log(n))$ .
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] This algorithm presorts *n* points in each of *k* dimensions using an $O(n\log(n))$ sort such as Heapsort or Mergesort prior to building the tree.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] It then maintains the order of these *k* presorts during tree construction and thereby avoids finding the median at each level of subdivision.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] One adds a new point to a *k*-d tree in the same way as one adds an element to any other search tree.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] First, traverse the tree, starting from the root and moving to either the left or the right child depending on whether the point to be inserted is on the "left" or "right" side of the splitting plane.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Once you get to the node under which the child should be located, add the new point as either the left or right child of the leaf node, again depending on which side of the node's splitting plane contains the new node.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Adding points in this manner can cause the tree to become unbalanced, leading to decreased tree performance.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] The rate of tree performance degradation is dependent upon the spatial distribution of tree points being added, and the number of points added in relation to the tree size.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] If a tree becomes too unbalanced, it may need to be re-balanced to restore the performance of queries that rely on the tree balancing, such as nearest neighbour searching.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] To remove a point from an existing *k*-d tree without breaking the invariant, the easiest way is to form the set of all nodes and leaves from the children of the target node and recreate that part of the tree.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Another approach is to find a replacement for the point removed.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] First, find the node R that contains the point to be removed.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] For the base case, where R is a leaf node, no replacement is required.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] For the general case, find a replacement point, say p , from the subtree rooted at R .
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] For finding a replacement point, if R discriminates on x (say) and R has a right child, find the point with the minimum x value from the subtree rooted at the right child.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Otherwise, find the point with the maximum x value from the subtree rooted at the left child.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Balancing a *k*-d tree requires care because *k*-d trees are sorted in multiple dimensions, so the tree-rotation technique cannot be used to balance them as this may break the invariant.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Several variants of balanced *k*-d trees exist.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] They include divided *k*-d tree, pseudo *k*-d tree, K-D-B-tree, hB-tree and Bkd-tree.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Many of these variants are adaptive k-d trees.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] The nearest neighbour search (NN) algorithm aims to find the point in the tree that is nearest to a given input point.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] This search can be done efficiently by using the tree properties to quickly eliminate large portions of the search space.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Once the algorithm reaches a leaf node, it checks the node point and if the distance is better than the "current best", that node point is saved as the "current best".
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] The algorithm checks whether there could be any points on the other side of the splitting plane that are closer to the search point than the current best.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] In concept, this is done by intersecting the splitting hyperplane with a hypersphere around the search point that has a radius equal to the current nearest distance.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Since the hyperplanes are all axis-aligned this is implemented as a simple comparison to see whether the distance between the splitting coordinate of the search point and current node is less than the distance (overall coordinates) from the search point to the current best.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] If the hypersphere doesn't intersect the splitting plane, then the algorithm continues walking up the tree, and the entire branch on the other side of that node is eliminated.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] When the algorithm finishes this process for the root node, then the search is complete.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Generally the algorithm uses squared distances for comparison to avoid computing square roots.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Additionally, it can save computation by holding the squared current best distance in a variable for comparison.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] The algorithm can be extended in several ways by simple modifications.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] It can provide the *k* nearest neighbours to a point by maintaining *k* current bests instead of just one.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] A branch is only eliminated when *k* points have been found and the branch cannot have points closer than any of the *k* current bests.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] It can also be converted to an approximation algorithm to run faster.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] For example, approximate nearest neighbour searching can be achieved by simply setting an upper bound on the number of points to examine in the tree or by interrupting the search process based upon a real time clock (which may be more appropriate in hardware implementations).
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] The nearest neighbour for points that are already in the tree can be achieved by not updating the refinement for nodes that give zero distance.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] As a result, this has the downside of discarding points that are not unique but are co-located with the original search point.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Approximate nearest neighbour is useful in real-time applications such as robotics due to the significant speed increase gained by not searching for the best point exhaustively.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] One of its implementations is best-bin-first search.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] A range search searches for ranges of parameters.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] For example, if a tree is storing values corresponding to income and age, then a range search might be something like looking for all members of the tree which have an age between 20 and 50 years and an income between 50,000 and 80,000.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Since k-d trees divide the range of a domain in half at each level of the tree, they are useful for performing range searches.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Analyses of binary search trees has found that the worst case time for range search in a *k*-dimensional *k*-d tree containing *n* nodes is given by the following equation.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] In low-dimensional spaces, the nearest point is an $O(\log(n))$ operation on average, in the case of randomly distributed points, although analysis in general is tricky.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] In high-dimensional spaces, the curse of dimensionality causes the algorithm to need to visit many more branches than in lower-dimensional spaces.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] In particular, when the number of points is only slightly higher than the number of dimensions, the algorithm is only slightly better than a linear search of all of the points.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] As a general rule, if the dimensionality is *k*, the number of points in the data, *n*, should be $n\gg 2^{k}$ .
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Otherwise, when *k*-d trees are used with high-dimensional data, most of the points in the tree will be evaluated and the efficiency is no better than exhaustive search, and, if a good-enough fast answer is required, approximate nearest-neighbour methods should be used instead.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] (In the worst case, consider a cloud of points distributed on the surface of a sphere centered at the origin.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] This may result in a nearest neighbor search failing to return a nearest neighbor, which means no points are within this maximum distance from the query point.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Instead of points, a *k*-d tree can also contain rectangles or hyperrectangles.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Thus range search becomes the problem of returning all rectangles intersecting the search rectangle.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] The tree is constructed the usual way with all the rectangles at the leaves.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] In an orthogonal range search, the *opposite* coordinate is used when comparing against the median.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] For example, if the current level is split along xhigh, we check the xlow coordinate of the search rectangle.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] If the median is less than the xlow coordinate of the search rectangle, then no rectangle in the left branch can ever intersect with the search rectangle and so can be pruned.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Otherwise both branches should be traversed.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] See also interval tree, which is a 1-dimensional special case.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] It is also possible to define a *k*-d tree with points stored solely in leaves.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] This form of *k*-d tree allows a variety of split mechanics other than the standard median split.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] The midpoint splitting rule selects on the middle of the longest axis of the space being searched, regardless of the distribution of points.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] This guarantees that the aspect ratio will be at most 2:1, but the depth is dependent on the distribution of points.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] A variation, called sliding-midpoint, only splits on the middle if there are points on both sides of the split.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Otherwise, it splits on point nearest to the middle.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Maneewongvatana and Mount show that this offers "good enough" performance on common data sets.
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Using sliding-midpoint, an approximate nearest neighbour query can be answered in $O\left({\tfrac {1}{{\epsilon \ }^{d}}}\log n\right)$ .
[src:faiss/k-d-tree] Approximate range counting can be answered in $O\left(\log n+{\left({\tfrac {1}{\epsilon \ }}\right)}^{d}\right)$ with this method.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Formally, the nearest neighbor (NN) search problem is defined as follows: given a set S of points in a space M and a query point $q\in M$ , find the closest point in S to q.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Donald Knuth in volume 3 of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1973) called it the **post-office problem**, referring to an application of assigning to a residence the nearest post office.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] A direct generalization of this problem is a k-NN search, where we need to find the k closest points.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Most commonly M is a metric space and dissimilarity is expressed as a distance metric, which is symmetric and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Even more common, M is taken to be the d-dimensional vector space where dissimilarity is measured using the Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance or other distance metric.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] However, the dissimilarity function can be arbitrary.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] One example is asymmetric Bregman divergence, for which the triangle inequality does not hold.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Various solutions to the NNS problem have been proposed.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The quality and usefulness of the algorithms are determined by the time complexity of queries as well as the space complexity of any search data structures that must be maintained.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The informal observation usually referred to as the curse of dimensionality states that there is no general-purpose exact solution for NNS in high-dimensional Euclidean space using polynomial preprocessing and polylogarithmic search time.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The simplest solution to the NNS problem is to compute the distance from the query point to every other point in the database, keeping track of the "best so far".
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] This algorithm, sometimes referred to as the naive approach, has a running time of *O*(*dN*), where *N* is the cardinality of *S* and *d* is the dimensionality of *S*.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] There are no search data structures to maintain, so the linear search has no space complexity beyond the storage of the database.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Naive search can, on average, outperform space partitioning approaches on higher dimensional spaces.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The absolute distance is not required for distance comparison, only the relative distance.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] In geometric coordinate systems the distance calculation can be sped up considerably by omitting the square root calculation from the distance calculation between two coordinates.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance comparison will still yield identical results.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Since the 1970s, the branch and bound methodology has been applied to the problem.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of Euclidean space, this approach encompasses spatial index or spatial access methods.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Several space-partitioning methods have been developed for solving the NNS problem.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Perhaps the simplest is the k-d tree, which iteratively bisects the search space into two regions containing half of the points of the parent region.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Queries are performed via traversal of the tree from the root to a leaf by evaluating the query point at each split.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Depending on the distance specified in the query, neighboring branches that might contain hits may also need to be evaluated.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] R-trees can yield nearest neighbors not only for Euclidean distance, but can also be used with other distances.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of general metric space, the branch-and-bound approach is known as the metric tree approach.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Particular examples include vp-tree and BK-tree methods.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Using a set of points taken from a 3-dimensional space and put into a BSP tree, and given a query point taken from the same space, a possible solution to the problem of finding the nearest point-cloud point to the query point is given in the following description of an algorithm.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] (Strictly speaking, no such point may exist, because it may not be unique.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] This may not be the case, but it is a good heuristic.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] After having recursively gone through all the trouble of solving the problem for the guessed half-space, now compare the distance returned by this result with the shortest distance from the query point to the partitioning plane.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] This latter distance is that between the query point and the closest possible point that could exist in the half-space not searched.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] If this distance is greater than that returned in the earlier result, then clearly there is no need to search the other half-space.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] If there is such a need, then you must go through the trouble of solving the problem for the other half space, and then compare its result to the former result, and then return the proper result.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] An approximate nearest neighbor search algorithm is allowed to return points whose distance from the query is at most c times the distance from the query to its nearest points.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The appeal of this approach is that, in many cases, an approximate nearest neighbor is almost as good as the exact one.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] In particular, if the distance measure accurately captures the notion of user quality, then small differences in the distance should not matter.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Proximity graph methods (such as navigable small world graphs and HNSW) are considered the current state-of-the-art for the approximate nearest neighbors search.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The methods are based on greedy traversing in proximity neighborhood graphs $G(V,E)$ in which every point $x_{i}\in S$ is uniquely associated with vertex $v_{i}\in V$ .
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The search for the nearest neighbors to a query *q* in the set *S* takes the form of searching for the vertex in the graph $G(V,E)$ .
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The basic algorithm – greedy search – works as follows: search starts from an enter-point vertex $v_{i}\in V$ by computing the distances from the query q to each vertex of its neighborhood $\{v_{j}:(v_{i},v_{j})\in E\}$ , and then finds a vertex with the minimal distance value.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] If the distance value between the query and the selected vertex is smaller than the one between the query and the current element, then the algorithm moves to the selected vertex, and it becomes new enter-point.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The algorithm stops when it reaches a local minimum: a vertex whose neighborhood does not contain a vertex that is closer to the query than the vertex itself.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] These works were preceded by a pioneering paper by Toussaint, in which he introduced the concept of a *relative neighborhood* graph.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Locality sensitive hashing (LSH) is a technique for grouping points in space into 'buckets' based on some distance metric operating on the points.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Points that are close to each other under the chosen metric are mapped to the same bucket with high probability.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The cover tree has a theoretical bound that is based on the dataset's doubling constant.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The bound on search time is *O*(*c*12 log *n*) where *c* is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] In the special case where the data is a dense 3D map of geometric points, the projection geometry of the sensing technique can be used to dramatically simplify the search problem.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] This approach requires that the 3D data is organized by a projection to a two-dimensional grid and assumes that the data is spatially smooth across neighboring grid cells with the exception of object boundaries.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] These assumptions are valid when dealing with 3D sensor data in applications such as surveying, robotics and stereo vision but may not hold for unorganized data in general.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] In practice this technique has an average search time of *O*(*1*) or *O*(*K*) for the *k*-nearest neighbor problem when applied to real world stereo vision data.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] In high-dimensional spaces, tree indexing structures become useless because an increasing percentage of the nodes need to be examined anyway.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] To speed up linear search, a compressed version of the feature vectors stored in RAM is used to prefilter the datasets in a first run.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The final candidates are determined in a second stage using the uncompressed data from the disk for distance calculation.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The VA-file approach is a special case of a compression based search, where each feature component is compressed uniformly and independently.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The optimal compression technique in multidimensional spaces is Vector Quantization (VQ), implemented through clustering.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The database is clustered and the most "promising" clusters are retrieved.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Huge gains over VA-File, tree-based indexes and sequential scan have been observed.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Also note the parallels between clustering and LSH.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] There are numerous variants of the NNS problem and the two most well-known are the *k*-nearest neighbor search and the ε-approximate nearest neighbor search.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] In some applications it may be acceptable to retrieve a "good guess" of the nearest neighbor.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] In those cases, we can use an algorithm which doesn't guarantee to return the actual nearest neighbor in every case, in return for improved speed or memory savings.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Often such an algorithm will find the nearest neighbor in a majority of cases, but this depends strongly on the dataset being queried.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Algorithms that support the approximate nearest neighbor search include locality-sensitive hashing, best bin first and balanced box-decomposition tree based search.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Nearest neighbor distance ratio does not apply the threshold on the direct distance from the original point to the challenger neighbor but on a ratio of it depending on the distance to the previous neighbor.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] It is used in CBIR to retrieve pictures through a "query by example" using the similarity between local features.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] More generally it is involved in several matching problems.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Fixed-radius near neighbors is the problem where one wants to efficiently find all points given in Euclidean space within a given fixed distance from a specified point.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance is assumed to be fixed, but the query point is arbitrary.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] For some applications (e.g. entropy estimation), we may have *N* data-points and wish to know which is the nearest neighbor *for every one of those N points*.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] This could, of course, be achieved by running a nearest-neighbor search once for every point, but an improved strategy would be an algorithm that exploits the information redundancy between these *N* queries to produce a more efficient search.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] As a simple example: when we find the distance from point *X* to point *Y*, that also tells us the distance from point *Y* to point *X*, so the same calculation can be reused in two different queries.
[src:faiss/nearest-neighbor-search] Given a fixed dimension, a semi-definite positive norm (thereby including every Lp norm), and *n* points in this space, the nearest neighbour of every point can be found in *O*(*n* log *n*) time and the *m* nearest neighbours of every point can be found in *O*(*mn* log *n*) time.
